            &lt;/div&gt;

            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;I worry that the parentheses are misleading on two counts: (1) they&apos;re not necessary  the comma operator doesn&apos;t have to be surrounded by parentheses; and (2) they could be confused with the parentheses around the argument list of a function call  but the comma in the argument list is not the comma operator.   However, fixing it is not entirely trivial.  Maybe: &lt;i&gt;In the statement: &lt;code&gt;expression1, expression2;&lt;/code&gt; first &lt;code&gt;expression1&lt;/code&gt; is evaluated, presumably for its side-effects (such as calling a function), then there is a sequence point, then &lt;code&gt;expression2&lt;/code&gt; is evaluated and the value returned&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/span&gt;

